{
  "texts": [
    "The two are connected with each other, insofar as information privacy is a way to protect citizens from undue scrutiny, negative judgments by others, pressures of conformity and possible intimidation.",
    "Voter information privacy prevents reputational damage in case of unpopular political preferences and allows citizens to deliberate and decide without undue influence from others.",
    "However, the view that voting preferences ought to remain secret is contested amongst political theorists.",
    "Brennan and Pettit argue in favour of \"unveiling the vote\", in order to make citizens \"publicly answerable for their electoral choices\" and able to defend them in a discursive way (Brennan and Pettit 1990).",
    "Lever, on the other hand, argues that \"the secret ballot suggests that people are entitled to keep at least some true facts about themselves to themselves, if they so wish, however interesting or useful such knowledge might be for others\" (Lever 2015)."
  ]
}